Here's a complete example of a Discord bot using **Discord.js v14** that has a single slash command called `ban`. This bot will allow users with the `BAN_MEMBERS` permission to ban a member from the server.

---

### ✅ Prerequisites

Make sure you have:

- Node.js installed (v16 or higher)
- `discord.js` installed (v14)
- A Discord bot token (you can get this from the [Discord Developer Portal](https://discord.com/developers/applications))

---

### 📦 Install Dependencies

```bash
npm init -y
npm install discord.js
```

---

### 📜 `index.js` (Main Bot File)

```js
const { Client, GatewayIntentBits, PermissionsBitField } = require('discord.js');

// Create a new client
const client = new Client({
  intents: [
    GatewayIntentBits.Guilds,
    GatewayIntentBits.GuildMembers,
    GatewayIntentBits.GuildMessages,
    GatewayIntentBits.MessageContent
  ]
});

// Replace with your bot token
const TOKEN = 'YOUR_BOT_TOKEN_HERE';

// Command data for the ban slash command
const banCommand = {
  name: 'ban',
  description: 'Ban a member from the server.',
  options: [
    {
      name: 'user',
      description: 'The user to ban.',
      type: 'USER',
      required: true
    },
    {
      name: 'reason',
      description: 'The reason for the ban.',
      type: 'STRING',
      required: false
    }
  ]
};

// Register the command
client.on('ready', () => {
  console.log(`Logged in as ${client.user.tag}!`);

  // Register the ban command
  client.application.commands.create(banCommand);
});

// Handle slash commands
client.on('interactionCreate', async (interaction) => {
  if (!interaction.isCommand()) return;

  const { commandName, options } = interaction;

  if (commandName === 'ban') {
    const user = options.getUser('user');
    const reason = options.getString('reason') || 'No reason provided';

    // Check if the user has permission to ban
    if (!interaction.memberPermissions.has(PermissionsBitField.Flags.BanMembers)) {
      return interaction.reply({
        content: 'You don\'t have permission to ban members.',
        ephemeral: true
      });
    }

    // Check if the user is the same as the bot
    if (user.id === client.user.id) {
      return interaction.reply({
        content: 'I can\'t ban myself.',
        ephemeral: true
      });
    }

    // Check if the user is a bot
    if (user.bot) {
      return interaction.reply({
        content: 'I can\'t ban another bot.',
        ephemeral: true
      });
    }

    // Ban the user
    try {
      await user.ban({ reason });
      interaction.reply({
        content: `${user.tag} has been banned. Reason: ${reason}`,
        ephemeral: true
      });
    } catch (error) {
      console.error('Error banning user:', error);
      interaction.reply({
        content: 'I couldn\'t ban that user. Please try again later.',
        ephemeral: true
      });
    }
  }
});

// Login the bot
client.login(TOKEN);
```

---

### 📌 Notes

- **Permissions**: The bot must have the `BAN_MEMBERS` permission in the server.
- **Ephemeral Replies**: All replies are ephemeral (only visible to the user who used the command) for security and privacy.
- **Reason**: The reason is optional and can be used for moderation logs.

---

### 🧪 Testing the Command

After running the bot, go to your server and type:

```
/ban @User [reason]
```

Example:
```
/ban @User123 spamming
```

---

