To draw a chessboard from a **FEN (Forsyth–Edwards Notation)** string in **LaTeX**, you can use the `TikZ` package, which is very powerful for creating diagrams and graphics. Below is a complete LaTeX code that:

- Parses a FEN string.
- Draws a standard 8x8 chessboard.
- Places the pieces according to the FEN notation.

---

### ✅ **Requirements:**
- You need to have the `tikz` package installed.
- You can use this in any LaTeX document by including the code.

---

### 🧾 **Example FEN Notation:**
Let's use the starting position FEN:
```
rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1
```

---

### 📄 **LaTeX Code:**

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usepackage{ifthen}

% Define the FEN string
\def\fenstring{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1}

\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5, transform shape]
    % Draw the chessboard
    \foreach \x in {0,...,7} {
        \foreach \y in {0,...,7} {
            \pgfmathsetmacro{\color}{int( (\x + \y) % 2 )}
            \ifthenelse{\equal{\color}{0}}{
                \draw[fill=white] (\x,\y) rectangle (\x+1,\y+1);
            }{
                \draw[fill=black] (\x,\y) rectangle (\x+1,\y+1);
            }
        }
    }

    % Function to place pieces
    \def\placepiece#1#2#3{
        \ifthenelse{\equal{#3}{p}}{
            \node at (#1,#2) {\textcolor{black}{\textsf{p}}};
        }{\ifthenelse{\equal{#3}{P}}{
            \node at (#1,#2) {\textcolor{white}{\textsf{P}}};
        }{\ifthenelse{\equal{#3}{r}}{
            \node at (#1,#2) {\textcolor{black}{\textsf{r}}};
        }{\ifthenelse{\equal{#3}{R}}{
            \node at (#1,#2) {\textcolor{white}{\textsf{R}}};
        }{\ifthenelse{\equal{#3}{n}}{
            \node at (#1,#2) {\textcolor{black}{\textsf{n}}};
        }{\ifthenelse{\equal{#3}{N}}{
            \node at (#1,#2) {\textcolor{white}{\textsf{N}}};
        }{\ifthenelse{\equal{#3}{b}}{
            \node at (#1,#2) {\textcolor{black}{\textsf{b}}};
        }{\ifthenelse{\equal{#3}{B}}{
            \node at (#1,#2) {\textcolor{white}{\textsf{B}}};
        }{\ifthenelse{\equal{#3}{q}}{
            \node at (#1,#2) {\textcolor{black}{\textsf{q}}};
        }{\ifthenelse{\equal{#3}{Q}}{
            \node at (#1,#2) {\textcolor{white}{\textsf{Q}}};
        }{\ifthenelse{\equal{#3}{k}}{
            \node at (#1,#2) {\textcolor{black}{\textsf{k}}};
        }{\ifthenelse{\equal{#3}{K}}{
            \node at (#1,#2) {\textcolor{white}{\textsf{K}}};
        }{\ifthenelse{\equal{#3}{-}}{}{
            \node at (#1,#2) {};
        }}}}}}}}}}}}}}
    }

    % Parse the FEN string
    \def\fenrow{0}
    \def\fencol{0}
    \def\fenpiece{}
    \def\fenrowcount{0}
    \def\fenrowindex{0}
    \def\fenrowdata{}

    % Split the FEN string into rows
    \foreach \row in \fenstring {
        \ifthenelse{\equal{\row}{/}}{
            \foreach \piece in \fenrowdata {
                \placepiece{\fencol}{\fenrow}{\piece}
                \pgfmathsetmacro{\fencol}{\fencol + 1}
            }
            \pgfmathsetmacro{\fenrow}{\fenrow + 1}
            \pgfmathsetmacro{\fencol}{0}
            \def\fenrowdata{}
        }{
            \ifthenelse{\equal{\row}{w}\or\equal{\row}{b}\or\equal{\row}{-}\or\equal{\row}{K}\or\equal{\row}{Q}\or\equal{\row}{R}\or\equal{\row}{B}\or\equal{\row}{N}\or\equal{\row}{P}\or\equal{\row}{p}\or\equal{\row}{r}\or\equal{\row}{n}\or\equal{\row}{b}\or\equal{\row}{q}\or\equal{\row}{k}}{
                \def\fenpiece{\row}
                \def\fenrowdata{\fenrowdata,\fenpiece}
            }{
                \pgfmathsetmacro{\count}{int(\row)}
                \foreach \i in {1,...,\count} {
                    \def\fenpiece{-}
                    \def\fenrowdata{\fenrowdata,\fenpiece}
                }
            }
        }
    }

    % Place the last row
    \foreach \piece in \fenrowdata {
        \placepiece{\fencol}{\fenrow}{\piece}
        \pgfmathsetmacro{\fencol}{\fencol + 1}
    }
\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}
```

---

### 📝 **How It Works:**

- The FEN string is parsed row by row.
- Each row is split into pieces or empty squares (`-`).
- The `placepiece` function places the piece on the board using TikZ.
- The board is drawn as a grid of 8x8 squares, alternating black and white.

---

### 📌 **Notes:**

- This code assumes the FEN string is in the format: `rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1`
- You can replace `\fenstring` with any valid FEN string.
- The code uses `textsf` for a simple sans-serif font. You can change it to `texttt` or `textbf` if needed.
- The board is drawn with a scale of `0.5` for better visibility. You can adjust it as needed.

---

### ✅ **To Use:**

1. Copy the code into a `.tex` file.
2. Compile it with `pdflatex` or any LaTeX compiler.
3. You will get a visual representation of the chessboard based on the FEN string.

